[[File:España - Toledo - Puerta de Alarcones 002.JPG|thumb|right|Puerta de Alarcones]] The '''Puerta de Alarcones''' is a [[city gate]] located in the city of [[Toledo, Spain|Toledo]], in [[Castile-La Mancha]], [[Spain]]. It is also known by the name of '''Puerta de Moaguía''', as cited in [[Mozarabic]] documents of 1216; and '''Puerta Alta de la Herrería''', because it is located at the end of the street where workshops dedicated to ironworks were located.
The gate was the forced access to Zocodover square before opening the ascent of the street of the calle de las Armas, by the lookout, so that, along with the [[Puerta del Sol, Toledo|Puerta del Sol]], it was adorned whenever Toledo was visited by some important personage, as a tribute to theirself to the passage of their cortege.<ref>{{cite web|author=Lourdes Morales Farfán|title=PUERTA DE ALARCONES|url=http://toledoguiaturisticaycultural.com/puerta-de-alarcones/}}</ref>
It is one of the oldest in the city, belonging to the [[Visigothic]] walled enclosure.<ref>{{cite book|author=Julio Porres Martín|title=Temas Toledanos|url=http://amigosderollopaterson.org/pdf/visitas/Puertas_y_Murallas.pdf|publisher=Diputación Provincial de Toledo|page=48}}</ref> The Puerta de Alarcones should have a also military crowning, which was destroyed, building itself.
A staircase has recently been discovered in its right-hand turret, whose gate existed earlier, deeper than this turret, which possibly gave access to the walls.
It was declared, along with rest of the Toledo's gates, walls and bridges, a national monument in December 1921.
