{{short description|Etruscan goddess of childbirth}} {{Infobox deity | type = Etruscan | name = Thalna | image = | caption = | deity_of = Goddess of [[childbirth]] | abode = | symbol = | consort = | parents = | siblings = | children = | mount = | other_names = | Greek_equivalent = }} In [[Etruscan mythology|Etruscan religion and myth]], '''Thalna''' was a divine figure usually regarded as a [[goddess]] of [[childbirth]]. Determinate gender, however, is not necessarily a characteristic of Etruscan deities, and Thalna is also either depicted as male,<ref>Nancy Thomson de Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth, Sacred History, and Legend'' (University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, 2006), pp. 21, 155.</ref> or seems to be identified as a male figure because of the placement of names around a scene. Her other functions include friendship and prophecy. Her name may mean "growth, bloom." She appears in Etruscan art in the company of [[Turan (mythology)|Turan]], [[Tinia]], and [[Menrva]].<ref>De Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth,'' p. 150.</ref>
On Etruscan [[bronze mirror]]s Thalna is present and looking on in scenes pertaining to birth and infancy.<ref>De Grummond, ''Etruscan Myth,'' pp. 61, with illustrations pp. 63, 65, 81.</ref>
